commit 82fbad8d49295afd7e581d9a8309a2d9c296d071
Author: Corey Thompson <coreyt@gmail.com>
Date:   Sun May 17 14:07:26 2026 -0500

    test(durability): AC-035a/b/c open-path corruption matrix
    
    Add four-fixture matrix wiring each `CorruptionKind` to a deterministic
    on-disk corruption: WAL sidecar with invalid header (new helper),
    page-0 magic flip (existing), interior b-tree byte flip (existing),
    and embedder-profile dimension = -1 (new helper).
    
    The matrix exposed two AC-035b routing gaps in `Engine::open` that the
    prior single test (`ac_006_*` in `lifecycle_observability.rs`) did not
    catch:
    
      - Page-0 magic flip surfaced via `pragma journal_mode = WAL` which
        routed it to `(WalReplayFailure, WalReplay)` instead of the
        documented `(HeaderMalformed, HeaderProbe)` row.
      - Page-1 b-tree byte flips trip during the WAL pragma for the same
        reason, masking the `(SchemaInconsistent, SchemaProbe)` row.
    
    Fix by ordering the open path so each `CorruptionKind` has its own
    dedicated probe step:
    
        HeaderProbe     -> PRAGMA application_id            (file header)
        SchemaProbe     -> SELECT COUNT(*) FROM sqlite_schema (b-tree)
        WalReplay       -> WAL sidecar magic + page-size pre-check,
                           then pragma journal_mode = WAL
        EmbedderIdentity -> check_embedder_profile
    
    The WAL sidecar pre-check is also a real reliability win: SQLite
    otherwise silently discards a malformed WAL, losing committed frames;
    we now refuse to open with `Corruption(WalReplayFailure)`.
    
    AC-035c (lock release + no fd / writer-thread residue) is linux-only
    and serialized via a static mutex so sibling tests in the same binary
    do not race the `/proc/self/{fd,task}` introspection.

