`probe_wal_sidecar()` uses `std::fs::read(&wal_path)` just to inspect the header. That makes `Engine.open` pull the full `-wal` sidecar into memory before SQLite does its own recovery work. On large unclean-shutdown WALs, this is a real open-path latency and RSS regression, and it directly risks the later AC-035 recovery-time budget. The schema-probe change is not the main latency concern here; the full-file WAL read is.

### 2. [medium] AC-034b drops some trials from the p99 instead of measuring across all `P-PWR-TRIALS`
Refs: [durability_soak.rs](/tmp/fdb-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:95), [durability_soak.rs](/tmp/fdb-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:128), [acceptance.md](/tmp/fdb-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z/dev/acceptance.md:568)

The harness records `lost_commit_ms: Option<u128>`, filters out `None`, then computes p99 on the surviving subset. It only requires that 90% of trials have at least one surviving commit. That is weaker than AC-034b’s stated measurement “report p99 across P-PWR-TRIALS trials,” and it means the parent never actually guarantees that each victim committed at least one row before `SIGKILL`.

### 3. [medium] AC-035c’s lock-release check is same-process, not sibling-process
Refs: [durability_open_path.rs](/tmp/fdb-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_open_path.rs:286), [acceptance.md](/tmp/fdb-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z/dev/acceptance.md:608)

The test reacquires `.lock` with a second fd in the same process and calls `flock` there. That is useful signal, but it is not the documented measurement, which requires process A to fail open and sibling process B to observe the lock as acquirable. Given the explicit AC text, this is a partial proof, not the full contract.

### 4. [low] The AC-034c ignored test is informative, but its body is a stub
Refs: [durability_soak.rs](/tmp/fdb-12-D-durability-harnesses-20260517T185755Z/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-engine/tests/durability_soak.rs:238)

The `#[ignore]` reason is good and points at the missing VM/sysrq substrate, but the body is intentionally empty. If someone clears `#[ignore]` without implementing the harness, the test would pass vacuously. This is not a current false green because it is ignored, but it is not a runnable placeholder.

**What passed on inspection**

- The `open_locked` reorder is directionally correct: header and schema probing now happen before `journal_mode=WAL`, which prevents header/page-1 and schema-btree corruption from being misclassified as WAL replay.
- AC-035b is asserted per fixture for all four documented rows. The tests do check exact `kind`, `stage`, `recovery_hint.code`, and `doc_anchor`, and the code-stability test checks both string equality and pointer equality for the `&'static str`.
- `serial_guard()` is taken by every test in `durability_open_path.rs`, not just the AC-035c tests, so same-binary thread/fd contamination is actually serialized away.
- The thread/fd residue assertions are consistent with the engine lifecycle: reader threads and the projection runtime are only created after `open_locked` succeeds, so a corruption return from `open_locked` should not leave engine-started threads behind.
- I did not find a meaningful large-schema regression from `SELECT COUNT(*) FROM sqlite_schema` by itself; in this repo the schema surface looks small and mostly fixed.

